  <header>
    <h1>Day 39 Lab</h1>
    <h2 class="lab-card">SIEM Hunt Mission ‚Äì Blue Team vs Suspicious Events in Splunk</h2>
  </header>

  <main>
    <div class="lab-card">
      <p><strong>Objective:</strong> Use Splunk to investigate suspicious activity in event logs and simulate blue team incident detection and analysis. Get hands-on with real SIEM queries and threat detection logic.</p>

      <h3>üõ† Tools Needed:</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><a href="https://www.splunk.com/en_us/download/splunk-cloud.html" target="_blank">Free Splunk Cloud Trial</a> (or Splunk Fundamentals Sandbox)</li>
        <li>Dataset: <a href="https://github.com/splunk/security_content" target="_blank">Splunk Security Content (Test Data)</a></li>
        <li>Basic Splunk Search Queries</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Step 1: Set Up Splunk Cloud</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Go to <a href="https://www.splunk.com/en_us/download/splunk-cloud.html" target="_blank">Splunk Cloud Free Trial</a></li>
        <li>Create an account and deploy a test instance</li>
        <li>Optional: Use their ‚ÄúSecurity Essentials‚Äù app to preload some test data</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Step 2: Load Sample Security Data</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Go to <a href="https://github.com/splunk/security_content" target="_blank">Splunk Security Content GitHub</a></li>
        <li>Download or clone a sample dataset (CSV or JSON)</li>
        <li>In Splunk Cloud, go to Settings ‚Üí Add Data ‚Üí Upload File</li>
        <li>Upload your dataset and index it under ‚Äúthreat_logs‚Äù</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Step 3: Begin Your Hunt</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Go to the Search & Reporting App in Splunk</li>
        <li>Try these example queries:
          <ul>
            <li><code>index=threat_logs sourcetype=* | stats count by src_ip, dest_ip, signature</code></li>
            <li><code>index=threat_logs action="blocked" OR action="denied"</code></li>
            <li><code>index=threat_logs signature="*powershell*"</code></li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li>Tag any of the following Indicators of Compromise (IOCs):
          <ul>
            <li>Suspicious IPs</li>
            <li>Unusual ports or protocols</li>
            <li>Command and control activity</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Step 4: Document Findings</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Write a short ‚ÄúIncident Report‚Äù with:
          <ul>
            <li>What you detected</li>
            <li>What query helped you find it</li>
            <li>Why it might be malicious</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li>Take a screenshot of your query and result set</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Step 5: Bonus Challenge</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Try building a dashboard in Splunk showing:
          <ul>
            <li>Top 5 source IPs</li>
            <li>Most common alert types</li>
            <li>Time chart of activity</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li>Use <code>timechart</code>, <code>top</code>, and <code>table</code> commands</li>
      </ul>

      <hr />
      <p><strong>Lab Summary:</strong> This lab puts you in the SOC analyst‚Äôs seat. You used Splunk to detect, investigate, and document malicious behavior in security logs. Blue teaming in real time!</p>
    </div>
  </main>
